story:
Thanks for supporting our  fundraising.

For anyone who knows us, they will know we are not runners so this is a real challenge for us both! We could say a real stretch (no pun intended!) At our work in W & R Barnett we are taking part in this health week initiative and will complete the 5k (in whatever time!) on Saturday 24th October. We decided we wanted to be more active ourselves but also to raise money for this great charity whilst remembering friends who are no longer with us but are very much in our thoughts. So to Mary and Julie, you are responsible for us doing this run!! Hope you laugh heartily and keep us safe! Anything you can support is greatly appreciated especially during these challenging times. And anything you donate will be matched through our charity fundraising scheme through W & R Barnett which we are so grateful for and will make such a difference to the charity!

Thank you- Anna & Gale

eventName: Deb and Chelle - Brave the Shave
story:
Back in 2013 Deb's son, Chelle's nephew was diagnosed with cancer. What started off as an apparent blood blister on his big toe, transpired to be tumour resulting in amputation. Part of this tumour had spilled into the blood and ended up forming a further tumour in his lung which was quickly operated on.

Fast forward 7 years, michael continues to be in remission however lightening has struck this family twice with his son, Deb's grandson being recently diagnosed with acute lymphoblastic leukaemia at the age of 4.

In the 3 weeks since being diagnosed Nathan has spent almost all of his time in hospital missing his first few weeks in reception and already received several blood and platelet transfusions to keep him strong enough for his chemo treatment.

As Nathan's hair begins to thin, Deb's and Chelle are bravely facing the clippers in hopes to raise money for Macmillan - I hope you can help them reach their goal!

eventName: Foxhills Macmilln Coffee Morning (Walk, Run or Wave)
story:
The Annual Foxhills Macmillan Coffee Morning!


The Coffee Morning can't take place as planned this year, but instead, we'd still like to raise some money for the charity, especially given the huge impact COVID has had on the charity which is under unprecedented demand for its services. We’d like to do a Macmillan Marathon. Between our residents, we need to Walk, Run or Cycle 60 laps of the Foxhill’s to complete 26.2 miles. Starting and finishing at the postbox with a ‘socially distanced’ coffee and cake at the end or outside your house (bring your own). 

*Just let me know how many laps your household complete! (Spot prize for a timed fastest lap and the house with the most laps!)

If you're unable to manage a lap, then please feel free to donate and enjoy a cake at home!

For a part of our BTEC Business Course, we have decided to hold a charity fundraising event for Macmillan Cancer Support. We have chosen Macmillan due to a few of our team members close family being affected by cancer. With everything going on in the world at the moment, we believe this is the least we could do to help out during these unprecedented times. It would really help out if you could give even the smallest donation to Macmillan as fundraising has been put on hold for those past few months.

This coffee morning will be held for students within the school on the 10th and 11th of November, where there will be drinks and cake available. It would be much appreciated to have outside donations to help out. You can donate at any time before the 11th November

story: So as most people that know me know, that my poor old dad has had an awful year with cancer, in January 2020 he was diagnosed with lung cancer and after a nasty operation and 1 lung gone we thought he’d kick its arse, unfortunately in July he was diagnosed with A secondary brain tumour, this we also thought may give him a few years. With out detail this is now not the case. So in support of Macmillan I have decided to chop all of my hair off and potentially donate my hair for a wig, I would appreciate even just £1 as this will all add up and help to support Macmillan in the wonderful work they are doing for all of its cancer patients, thank you for supporting me, much love Teresa xx

story:
We are heartbroken at the loss of our beloved mamma, Cristiana Angelini. A warm-hearted, talented, independent spirit, Cris will be missed by many.

At a time when paying our respects has been restricted, we know that Cristiana would have appreciated a donation towards The British Heart Foundation, rather than sending flowers. We hope that in so doing, part of her legacy will be in helping towards the charity's pioneering research to bring us closer to treatments and cure for heart and circulatory diseases. Thank you so much.

Rest in Peace Cristiana. Sogni, d'oro.

eventName: Watford, Hemel Hempstead and Borehamwood Guide Dogs Virtual Collection
story: As a result of the latest developments, Watford, Hemel Hempstead and Borehamwood Fundraising Branch are unable to go ahead with their normal collections planned together with other events in the coming months. We as a Fundraising Branch for Guide Dogs remains committed to supporting people with sight loss in our own local areas.  It has never been more important to come together online and support one another. We appreciate times are difficult right now, but for people with sight loss, social isolation can be their every day. By hosting a virtual collection for Guide Dogs, every pound you or your group raises will ensure we can continue to help people with sight loss and feel less alone, now and in the future. It costs £13 a day to support each of our life changing dogs. Any donation will be gratefully received.

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
Ten years ago, I started experiencing intermittent headaches.  As a mum of two, with a busy lifestyle, I assumed this was stress-related, until a routine eye test revealed the real cause. 

I remember the concerned look on the optician’s face, after he’d checked my eyes. He told me I had to go straight to Addenbrooke’s Hospital in Cambridge as my optic nerve was extremely inflamed.  Within 24 hours, I was having an emergency MRI scan and was told that the headaches were due to me having too much spinal fluid, which was crushing my optic nerve, and causing tunnel vision in both eyes. I just remember in that moment my world falling apart.  From then on, my husband had to take time off work to take me to appointments and I had to give up my job, which put financial strain on us.  I suddenly went from being a working mum, to a stay at home mum. I also brought my wedding forward by six months because I didn’t want to risk being a blind bride. After months of tests, I was diagnosed with Benign Intracranial Hypertension causing Papilledema and am now blind in my right eye with tunnel vision in my left, something which has been made easier by having a guide dog for support. I now have to take medication every day for the rest of my life to help maintain the vision I do have.  

When I qualified with my first guide dog Quaver, it gave me my freedom and my independence back.  Having a guide dog has meant I’ve been able to see my friends again and travel to places like London, without having someone there to hold my hand.

Guide Dogs have supported me so well and it is now that they need our support more than ever to continue their life changing work to help people like me to gain our independence again.  Our local fundraising group are not able to collect out and about at the moment due to current restrictions and so I invite you to donate via this page to contribute to the charity’s income.

Thank you.
title: Peterborough Guide Dogs Virtual Collection

story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story: Great Ormond Street Hospital supports seriously ill children from all over the UK. Since 2012, Premier Inn and Restaurants have been proud partners of Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity and we know our passionate teams have taken part in many brilliant fundraising events as well as volunteering at national events around the country and at the hospital. During these uncertain times our teams continue to achieve incredible things, challenging themselves to conquer their Everest and take care of their wellbeing. We are looking to continue the fantastic fundraising achieved through our partnership by supporting our teams in their creative and dedicated ways of personal achievement. We are #innthistogether and together, we can continue our incredible work.

charity.name: Cancer Research UK
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 1089464, Scotland SC041666
story: Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page. Katherine and I want to raise awareness as well as money for less researched forms of cancer, such as childhood and prostate cancer. These forms of cancer have less funding than other types of more prominent cancers, with childhood cancers only getting £4 million in funding and prostate cancer getting £12 million in funding when breast cancer gets £30 million. It is a disease that has affected everyone and needs to be continually addressed until a cure can be found! Thank you for supporting our cause and we look forward to seeing you at one of our quizzes at half term on Zoom :).

story:
Keith lived with cancer for 11 years, and for the majority of it, with a lust for life and not letting it get to him or feeling sorry for himself. He outlived his prognosis by nearly 10 years and we thought he was invincible. It finally got the better of him and the Marie Curie in Edinburgh looked after him.  He will be sorely missed by so many. He loved so many things, family, friends, Hibs, travel, wine, music, culture, history to name a few. A talented guitarist. Lived in Japan for many years and worked as an investment manager. This doesn’t even begin to touch the surface of him. Kind, intelligent and a gent. We love and miss you.

story:
Maria, known to many of us as Mary, unfortunately lost her battle with cancer on 4th October 2020. 

Mary was loved so much by so many, with hundreds of friends around the globe. She was the family oracle, who made Delancey Street not only her home, but home to anyone and everyone who wanted to stay, be it for a night or a few years. Her generosity was unmatched by anyone I know, and all who knew her would say the same. 

After months of family caring for her while she was able to be at home, Marie Curie then kindly opened their doors to her at their Hampstead hospice in her final days. In lieu of flowers, we would be very grateful if you could donate to Marie Curie as a thank you for their help in her time of need and endless efforts to make her comfortable. 

The family are so grateful that Mary was able to end her days in a caring, wonderful environment and we hope your donations will reflect this and enable them to provide the same amazing care and comfort to others in need in the future.

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Health and Safety training is required, but due to social distancing restrictions it is not possible to do it at the station so they need to hire a hall. 

We are doing 6 virtual Fish Suppers between 6 local households and pooling the funds.

We have a fab raffle prize see photo. Craftsman made beech chopping board, measuring 20 inches/17inches. Especially made just for us! And it may come with a few surprises!! Raffle tickets are £2 each. Get in touch with me tell me how many you need and the name and phone number of the person and I will tell you the numbers they are allocated. Suggest payment using this group page.

Any donations would be appreciated!

All proceeds to go to Criccieth RNLI

Thank you.

story:
Betty Stogs  and her team are taking on the Challenge of rowing a raft from Truro to Falmouth on Sunday 18th October in aid of her favorite charities - the RNLI and the Children's Hospice South West .

The raft has been designed to ensure it meets all safety requirements including social distancing.

Betty has supported the RNLI for many years and the money raised from this challenge will help support the work of the Lifeboats in the South West and in particular Falmouth Lifeboat Station.

Like all charities the RNLI has been significantly impacted by Covid-19 but despite this it has managed to maintain a 24-hour search and rescue service. The RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea and with your support they will always be there to answer that call.

story:
Why the challenge - 13 In 13?

On the 31st December 2019 I completed a runstreak of at least one mile every day in 2019.  Having gone from being a beginner runner to completing Couch to 5k, 10k & a half marathon I had caught the infamous 'running bug' & also completed a huge personal challenge, all inspired by my brother in law Steve, who devastatingly passed away in December 2018 from a Grade 4 brain tumour, aged just 44.

In 2021 I want to challenge myself again by completing 13 different challenges within 13 months, starting in December 2020. As I go I'll also hopefully raise vital funds for two charities, chosen for quite different reasons but equally important.

Why the RNLI?

Too many people are still drowning. 

A big chunk of my challenges will be made up of a swimming element, something that I take for granted at being able to do. Not everyone has had the opportunity to learn to swim, whether as a child or an adult, & even the most experienced swimmers can find themselves in an unexpected situation, where they require emergency help.

As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search & rescue right around the UK & Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK & Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams & educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

story:

Your support is much appreciated.

Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
charity.registrationNumber: 1072612 (England & Wales) and SC043677 (Scotland)
eventName: Online Christmas Present Car Boot Sale
story:
I am fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems.
Just £30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just £43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers.
The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members.
Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to my page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.
title: My page to help a generation of children affected by Coronavirus

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation.

We provide emergency assistance to people affected by armed conflict, epidemics and natural or man-made disasters, without discrimination and irrespective of race, religion, gender or political affiliation. 

We work in over 70 countries and go to the places where others cannot or choose not to go.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
